WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.240
Hi, I'm Norman Wildberger, and today we're going&nbsp;
to talk, as part of our foundation of mathematics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:12.240 --> 00:00:18.870
series, about the greatest single discovery&nbsp;
and innovation in the history of mathematics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:18.870 --> 00:00:27.420
and science put together. It is the Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;
number system that is currently taught to students&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:27.420 --> 00:00:34.110
everywhere around the world. Let me remind you&nbsp;
that our approach so far to numbers has been as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:34.110 --> 00:00:40.620
a string of ones. So, a natural number is just a&nbsp;
string of ones, and it's a sequence that carries&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:40.620 --> 00:00:48.030
on endlessly like this. It becomes pretty clear&nbsp;
when we're working with numbers this way that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.030 --> 00:00:54.705
larger and larger numbers become awkward to deal&nbsp;
with, and every civilization has had to innovate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:54.705 --> 00:01:04.350
to find ways of shortening these large numbers.&nbsp;
So, we're going to talk today about a precursor&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:04.350 --> 00:01:10.800
to the Hindu-Arabic system: the Roman numeral&nbsp;
system. And that's a natural stepping stone from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:10.800 --> 00:01:15.690
this sort of primitive basic understanding&nbsp;
of numbers to the one we currently have.

00:01:17.550 --> 00:01:21.570
Alright, so the idea, for so long, to go to&nbsp;
the Roman system—and this is a simplified Roman&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:21.570 --> 00:01:27.060
system, not the full one that they used—is to&nbsp;
introduce other symbols for larger denominations.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:27.060 --> 00:01:34.200
Just as in commerce, we don't want to run the&nbsp;
economy using $1 bills; we also want $10 bills,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:34.200 --> 00:01:43.440
$100 bills, $1,000 bills if necessary. So, the&nbsp;
Romans introduced new symbols for larger numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:43.440 --> 00:01:51.360
of ones and larger numbers of other numbers. So,&nbsp;
the basic step is to take ten ones, a string of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:51.360 --> 00:02:02.160
10 ones, and call it 10, and we denote that by the&nbsp;
symbol X. Then we agree that if we have 10 X's or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:02.160 --> 00:02:11.190
10 tens, we denote that by the symbol C, calling&nbsp;
it a hundred. Ten hundreds are denoted with an M,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:11.190 --> 00:02:17.520
called a thousand, and we can introduce further&nbsp;
symbols if we want to. So now the idea is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:17.520 --> 00:02:21.450
instead of having a huge string of&nbsp;
ones, we group those ones into tens,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:21.450 --> 00:02:25.560
and then we group the tens into hundreds,&nbsp;
and we group the hundreds into thousands,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:25.560 --> 00:02:33.240
and so on. So, we can write a number like&nbsp;
this: two M's, four C's, five ones—that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:33.240 --> 00:02:43.170
would be the number 2405. In this case, there&nbsp;
are no tens in that number, and we agree that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:43.170 --> 00:02:49.260
when we do this, we're going to list the bigger&nbsp;
denominations first: thousands, hundreds, tens,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:49.260 --> 00:02:55.650
and then ones. And that's any ten symbols of&nbsp;
the same kind replaced by a bigger symbol. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:55.650 --> 00:03:01.650
we're not allowed to have ten or eleven or twelve&nbsp;
C's in a row; we would then agree that we're going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:01.650 --> 00:03:07.890
to replace 10 of those C's with an M, or any&nbsp;
ten X's are replaced by a C. So that means that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:07.890 --> 00:03:18.630
effectively the maximum number of symbols that we&nbsp;
have in a row in such an expression is nine. This&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:18.630 --> 00:03:24.300
is the simplified Roman numeral system which&nbsp;
was in use for, of course, thousands of years,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:24.300 --> 00:03:29.130
and it serves as a very good shortcut to&nbsp;
our basic understanding of natural numbers.

00:03:29.130 --> 00:03:37.170
Alright, so the Indian mathematicians introduced&nbsp;
a couple of key innovations. What they did is they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:37.170 --> 00:03:45.810
first of all had names and symbols for all the&nbsp;
numbers between what we call now 1 and 9: 1, 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:45.810 --> 00:03:56.310
3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, and 9. And more importantly, we&nbsp;
have these symbols to represent them. So, these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.310 --> 00:04:00.750
are just new symbols; they're somewhat arbitrary,&nbsp;
it doesn't really matter which ones we use,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.750 --> 00:04:08.010
but we agree to use these ones. These symbols&nbsp;
represent these strings of ones. In addition,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:08.010 --> 00:04:15.240
we're also going to need to have a new symbol for&nbsp;
nothing. So, the new symbol called zero, denoted&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:15.240 --> 00:04:22.860
by a circle, stands for nothing. And now the idea&nbsp;
of the Hindu-Arabic number system is very simple:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.860 --> 00:04:31.880
we take a natural number expressed in Roman form&nbsp;
like this, and what we do is we record the number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:31.880 --> 00:04:39.710
of units of each size starting from the right. So,&nbsp;
we record how many ones there are. In this case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:39.710 --> 00:04:44.600
there are five ones, so we write down a five.&nbsp;
Then we go to tens: how many tens are there?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:44.600 --> 00:04:51.080
There are zero tens. In this case, we write down&nbsp;
a zero. There are four hundreds; we write down&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:51.080 --> 00:04:59.300
a four. There are two thousands; we write down&nbsp;
a two. So, this represents this Roman numeral,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:59.300 --> 00:05:05.270
which, of course, represents a huge string of ones&nbsp;
with two thousand four hundred and five ones. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:05.270 --> 00:05:10.970
the key innovation here is first of all that&nbsp;
we are only using the numbers from zero to nine&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:10.970 --> 00:05:16.640
in each place because there's at most nine of&nbsp;
any string allowed. If there were ten or more,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:16.640 --> 00:05:22.370
we would replace it with one of the next bigger.&nbsp;
And the second is that we're allowed to use zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:22.370 --> 00:05:30.620
to hold the place, in other words, to record the&nbsp;
number of denominations at that particular size.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:30.620 --> 00:05:37.460
Zero tens, in this case, is very important. So, we&nbsp;
keep the ones, tens, hundreds, and thousands all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:37.460 --> 00:05:46.190
straight. The Hindu-Arabic number system allows&nbsp;
us to deal with large numbers very effectively,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:46.190 --> 00:05:52.850
and one of the interesting innovations is&nbsp;
that powers of 10 become important. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.850 --> 00:06:00.350
the first new symbol is this one: zero, which&nbsp;
stands for zero ones and one ten. That's our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:00.350 --> 00:06:08.720
new symbol for the actual number ten, no longer&nbsp;
X. One hundred, which is zero ones, zero tens,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:08.720 --> 00:06:14.510
and one hundred, is now represented by this&nbsp;
expression: 100. And we also can write it as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:14.510 --> 00:06:21.980
ten times ten or ten squared. In the same way,&nbsp;
we have a thousand represented by ten cubed—ten&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:21.980 --> 00:06:28.010
times ten times ten. Ten thousand: ten to the&nbsp;
fourth. One hundred thousand: ten to the fifth.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:28.010 --> 00:06:36.140
And one million: ten to the sixth. And we could&nbsp;
keep on going. So, if we have a number like 327,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:36.140 --> 00:06:45.870
what that is really, in terms of tens, is there&nbsp;
are seven ones, two tens, and three hundreds. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.870 --> 00:06:52.140
we can always rewrite a number like this, if&nbsp;
we need to, as multiples of powers of ten.

00:06:52.140 --> 00:06:56.850
So, what are the advantages of the&nbsp;
Hindu-Arabic number system? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:56.850 --> 00:07:05.070
first of all, it's very compact. Secondly, it&nbsp;
simplifies arithmetic dramatically. In ancient&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:05.070 --> 00:07:11.430
times, only very well-educated people could&nbsp;
hope to do simple multiplications, and even&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:11.430 --> 00:07:16.350
most reasonably complicated multiplications&nbsp;
could only be done approximately because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:16.350 --> 00:07:22.830
of the cumbersome nature of the Roman and&nbsp;
other systems. With Hindu-Arabic arithmetic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:22.830 --> 00:07:29.160
even young people in primary school can learn&nbsp;
how to multiply big numbers by hand, and that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:37.050
an important skill. It allows approximation in a&nbsp;
very effective way, and we'll talk about that when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:37.050 --> 00:07:44.400
we extend the Hindu-Arabic system to decimals.&nbsp;
This is a key point in the importance of this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:44.400 --> 00:07:51.720
system for scientific work. So, this is really&nbsp;
a fabulous innovation. One can't overestimate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:51.720 --> 00:07:58.170
how important this was to the modern world. Next&nbsp;
time, we're going to talk about how arithmetic is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:58.170 --> 00:08:05.340
transformed using this system. I hope you'll join&nbsp;
me. I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

00:08:05.340 --> 00:08:07.460
Let me know if you need any further assistance!

